dataset.measure: Estimated Annual Rate- Children 0 to 17 Yrs Old
dataset.how_calculated: Estimate is based on the number of hospitalizations for urgent asthma associated with the difference in air quality for indicator years relative to natural background (modeled air quality levels under no man made air pollution emissions).  Estimate is calculated using the acute risk of hospitalization for urgent asthma from the Silverman et al 2010 study conducted on NYC residents. Neighborhood estimates expressed as annual cases per 100,000 residents under 18 years of age.

show_disparities_node.disparitiesPagetext: When population health or the quality of living environments varies by population characteristics such as income or race, there is disparity. One way to visualize disparity is to chart indicators of health or environment across levels of neighborhood poverty. We categorized neighborhoods as high, medium or low poverty. Then we took the median of the neighborhood-specific values in each category. The median is the middle of the sorted group of values.

show_disparities_data.Measure: Estimated Annual Rate- Children 0 to 17 Yrs Old

Estimate is calculated using the acute risk of hospitalization for urgent asthma from the Silverman et al 2010 study conducted on NYC residents. Neighborhood estimates expressed as annual cases per 100,000 residents under 18 years of age.
info.info_source: US EPA Air Quality System; Silverman RA, Ito K (2010) J Allergy Clin Immun 125(2):367373,New York State Statewide Planning and Research Cooperative System (SPARCS); US Census

info.info_how_calculated: Neighborhoods are ranked according to the percent of people whose annual income falls below 100% of the federal poverty level. Rankings are then divided into 3 approximately equal groupings of low, medium and high poverty.
